                    <li><span><strong>Media Contact:</strong></span><span>Ms. Faith Adhiambo | Communications Officer-Agenda 2063 | African union Commission | E-mail: <a href="mailto:OchiengJ@africa-union.org">OchiengJ@africa-union.org</a></span></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
        <h4 class="center">AfCFTA Implementation</h4>
        <p class="para">gives a system for the liberalization of exchange in merchandise and administrations, and a component for debate settlement. For exchange in merchandise, the assertion sets the way for killing taxes on 90 percent of item categories. Nations can actualize tax decreases over a longer period within the case of delicate merchandise or keep up existing tariffs—where the items are excluded—for the remaining 10 percent of item categories (duty lines). The convention on exchange in products incorporates adds on duty concessions, rules of root, traditions participation, exchange help, non-tariff boundaries, specialized obstructions to exchange, sterile and phytosanitary measures, and travel and exchange cures.</p>
        <p class="para">Competition policy, investment, and intellectual property rights will all be discussed.</p>
        <p class="para">(on e-commerce) to promote agri-food trade by, for example, helping to the expansion of agricultural production, food processing, value chain development, food access, distribution networks, and payment systems</p>
        <h4 class="center">Benefits To The Continent</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>African youth will get better quality jobs</strong></li>
            <p>African youth aged 15 to 24 face two times the unemployment rate of adults, with country-by-country variations. Because the manufacturing and agro products that benefit the most from the AfCFTA demand more labour, the AfCFTA will provide significant employment for Africa's burgeoning youth. As youthful and developing endeavours pick up get to the biggest single showcase within the world nowadays, their generation capacity will increment, driving to more employment. For case, a Malian rice rancher based close the border with Niger may start to trade their abundance deliver to the adjacent capital of Niamey. This would incentivise them to utilize more beneficial assets, counting cultivate work. Moreover, citizens will be superior situated to get to employments in more master areas due to more versatility over countries.</p>
            <li><strong>African businesses will become more productive and competitive</strong></li>
            <p>Gaining access to a larger market allows small enterprises to increase production, recognize different product types, and maybe profit from economies of scale, such as lower input costs. For example, a Nigerian shoe manufacturer may set up production in another country with unlimited calfskin and reduced power prices without losing the right to sell in its home country.</p>
            <li><strong>African consumers can purchase goods at cheaper prices</strong></li>
            <p>Expanded competition among African businesses and get to more assortment of products from neighbouring nations would drive costs down, permitting for superior get to tall quality items at reasonable costs. According to estimates, if the AfCFTA is fully implemented, Africa will have a combined consumer and trade investment of $6.7 trillion by 2030, up from roughly $2.7 trillion in 2015. Families living on the brink of poverty benefit from increased access to a wider range of goods at lower prices.</p>
            <li><strong>African women will be empowered</strong></li>
            <p>More than two-thirds of informal cross-border traders are women. When women cross borders to commerce, they are subjected to exorbitant tariffs, delays, corruption, and even sexual abuse. Free mobility under the AfCFTA would alleviate these issues, boosting productivity by lowering women's barriers to expanding their market beyond national borders.</p>
            <li><strong>African governments will make more revenue</strong></li>
            <p>Reduced trade costs within Africa might practically quadruple intra-regional trade, especially if non-tariff barriers to trade are reduced. Economic integration will enhance Africa's overall economic output, putting the continent on the path to rapid and inclusive economic development, albeit the advantages will differ by country. Due to inefficient taxes on modest levels of existing intra-regional commerce, declines in government revenue from import levies are currently expected to be minor, at 0.03 percent of GDP. However, if non-tariff barriers are removed, revenue will rise because of increased economic production.</p>
        </ul>
        <h4 class="center">Benefits To SMMEs</h4>
        <p>The AfCFTA, according to Amrote Abdella, Regional Director, Microsoft 4Afrika, is an exciting game changer deal for the countries that have signed on. “By converting spending power into economic development, it has the potential to stimulate innovation, growth, and productivity across the continent, but particularly for the region's SME component. Simplifying customs procedures and reducing red tape could result in huge revenue increases for SMEs. SMEs may benefit from the anticipated trade boom by enhancing their ability to quickly scale up using digital skills.</p>
        <h6><strong>Case Study</strong></h6>
        <p>Ghanaian business visionaries, who are energetic almost end of the of their companies inside the setting of the African Mainland Free Exchange Zone (AfCFTA), are being empowered to guarantee that their trade substances are formalized to harvest the complete benefits of the agreement. The as it were way Little and Medium Endeavours (SMEs) can take advantage of the AfCFTA is for SMEs “to be formalized from the exceptionally foundation.” Dr. Amanobea Boateng, the Chief Official Officer of Wander Capital and the author of Women’s DNA Support and Establishment, said this on the on-air arrangement of the Citi Trade Celebration on the Citi Breakfast Appear on Monday, June 21, 2021.</p>
        <p>Talking on the subject “Making your Trade Export-ready’, she said, “a lot of SMEs are within the casual segment. In case this [AfCFTA] is a region you need to participate in, you wish to be formalized. You wish to be enrolled with the proper specialists. You wish to guarantee that your frameworks, accounts, and record-keeping are done legitimately and up to date; so, all of that has to be in place,” Dr. Boateng said. She included that not as it were must the trade proprietors formalize their operations, but they must familiarize themselves with commercial exercises within the gigantic African market. Key among the zones they must be educated approximately incorporate culture, dialect potential, target showcase, inclinations, and controls to make strides forms towards trading their items or services. “If you are a business that is not going to export, how are you going to be competitive when others come into the market?” Dr. Boateng said, emphasizing the need of developing and current enterprises focusing on exportation. If you haven't thought it through, it will be difficult.” She said, in as much as there are businesses in Africa, there may be differences. While conceding that they may have similar items, she accepts businesses must be fascinated by looking for data around competitors in those diverse nations whereas they work in Ghana. To address this, the CEO of Women’s DNA Finance and Establishment said, “you got to advise yourself”. “If you need to export, and it is the AfCFTA you need to be portion of, go and discover approximately it. Go to the pertinent specialists. You will be able go to the Secretariat and get the data. In common, if you need to take part within the common showcase, discover out from those markets,” she underlined.</p>
        <h4 class="center">Importance of Intra-Continental Trade</h4>
        <p>The Comprehensive Africa Agriculture Development Programme (CAADP) complements the AfCFTA by assisting in enhancing agricultural productivity, market access, and innovation. The AfCFTA can create opportunities to "build a continental agribusiness plan" with the private sector as a catalyst for sustainable agricultural growth when used in conjunction with the African Union Continental Agribusiness Strategy.</p>
        <p>The AfCFTA will rely on well-functioning farmers' organizations to ensure that key agri-food stakeholders are involved in discussions and decision-making to deliver new ideas for increasing agricultural productivity and development.</p>
        <p>In addition to implementing other Agendas and Programs such as the Accelerated Industrial Development for Africa (AIDA) and the Program Infrastructure Development for Africa (PIDA), countries will need to implement national accompanying policies to turn the AfCFTA's potential into concrete opportunities (PIDA).</p>
        <p>Professor Benedict Oramah, President of Afreximbank, spoke about the need of encouraging intra-African trade in a paper released during the Intra-African Trade Fair (IATF) in Cairo, Egypt, in December 2018.
            'As a flagship project of the African Union's Agenda 2063: The Africa We Want, the AfCFTA will bring together 55 African countries with a combined population of more than 1.2 billion people and a combined gross domestic product (GDP) of more than $2.5 trillion, making it the continent's largest free trade area since the World Trade Organisation's founding (WTO). He further stated 'An integrated African market is likely to see greater FDI flows to participating economies, shifting FDI from natural resources to industry and manufacturing as investors seek to take advantage of economies of scale associated with increasing market size. Implementation of the AfCFTA in the context of the broader Motivation 2063 will also improve African economies' integration into the global economy and strengthen the method of engagement between Africa and its primary trading partners, both multilaterally within the WTO system and bilaterally with other trading partners, particularly the creating South whose share of worldwide exchange has expanded essentially over the final few decades.’
        </p>
